 St Botolphbridge, Huntingdonshire, England":"Orton Longueville, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beatrice","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Angelo, Attilio, Dante, Luigi, Pellegrino, Pietro, Rocco, Salvatore, Vincenzo.","Italian and English: from a female personal name borne in honor of a 4th-century Christian saint, martyred together with her brothers Simplicius and Faustinus. Her name was originally <i>Viātrix</i> meaning ‘traveler’ (a feminine form of <i>viātor</i>, from <i>via</i> ‘way’), a name adopted by early Christians in reference to the journey through life, and Christ's description of himself as ‘the way, the life, and the truth’; it was later altered as a result of folk etymological association with Latin <i>beatus</i> ‘blessed’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beets","meanings":["Dutch: mainly a habitational name from either of two villages called Beets, in North Holland and Friesland.","English: variant of <b>Beet</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Bete</i>, a pet form of <i>Betris</i> (see   Beatrice  ). In East Anglia, however, where the name is concentrated, it is of Dutch origin (see 1 above), as evidenced by the census of 1881. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Probably an altered form of German   Beetz  ."]},{"name":"Baeten","meanings":["Dutch: metronymic from a short form of the female personal name<i>Beatrix</i> (see   Beatrice  )."]},{"name":"Beat","meanings":["Scottish (Angus) and English: variant of <b>Beet</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Bete</i>, a pet form of <i>Betris</i> (see   Beatrice  ). Compare   Beets  ."]},{"name":"Beeton","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire and Suffolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Beton</i> (a diminutive of <i>Bete</i>, a pet form 